00:11:54,847 --> 00:11:57,111
but you can kiss
your social life good-bye.

202
00:12:01,253 --> 00:12:03,187
Hi, Homer.
Hi.

203
00:12:15,468 --> 00:12:18,232
I don't let anybody
copy my homework.

204
00:12:18,304 --> 00:12:20,898
I don't wanna copy
your homework.

205
00:12:20,973 --> 00:12:23,635
Um,

206
00:12:23,709 --> 00:12:25,734
do you know anything
about rockets?

207
00:12:25,811 --> 00:12:27,369
Of course I do.

208
00:12:27,446 --> 00:12:30,244
Uh, you wanna come with me
over to the library?

209
00:12:30,316 --> 00:12:32,284
No.

210
00:12:38,824 --> 00:12:41,258
[Students Murmuring]

211
00:12:47,166 --> 00:12:49,157
What do you wanna know
about rockets?

212
00:12:49,235 --> 00:12:51,829
Everything.

213
00:12:54,039 --> 00:12:59,409
Well, rocketry was actually
invented by the Chinese
as early as 1,000 A.D.

214
00:12:59,478 --> 00:13:01,639
And, supposedly,
they were quite sophisticated.

215
00:13:01,714 --> 00:13:04,649
[Chattering Continues]

216
00:13:07,186 --> 00:13:09,814
Potassium chlorate and sulphur.

217
00:13:09,889 --> 00:13:13,052
Uh, well,
what'd you use?

218
00:13:14,293 --> 00:13:16,784
Uh, somethin' like that.

219
00:13:16,862 --> 00:13:19,023
<i>[Homer]</i>
<i>Hey, Quentin, this is great.</i>

220
00:13:19,098 --> 00:13:22,966
This is exactly... We have
everything we need in here.

221
00:13:23,035 --> 00:13:24,969
Roy Lee,
drive me to my house.

222
00:13:25,037 --> 00:13:28,063
<i>We can use my basement.</i>
Yeah, at least nobody'll
see us down there.

223
00:13:28,140 --> 00:13:30,768
Go, go, go.
<i>[Engine Turning Over]</i>

224
00:13:30,843 --> 00:13:33,710
Come on.
<i>[Quentin]</i>
<i>You got a loose choke cable.</i>

225
00:13:33,779 --> 00:13:35,713
You hear that?

226
00:13:35,781 --> 00:13:39,012
The butterfly valve
isn't closin' all the way.

227
00:13:42,855 --> 00:13:45,915
Uh, last year I built
an internal combustion engine...

228
00:13:45,991 --> 00:13:48,118
and entered it
in the science fair.

229
00:13:48,194 --> 00:13:50,992
<i>Yeah, well, you wouldn't happen</i>
<i>to have it on you, would you?</i>

230
00:13:51,063 --> 00:13:52,997
<i># Gonna find her #</i>

231
00:13:54,466 --> 00:13:57,663
<i># Gonna find her #</i>

232
00:13:57,736 --> 00:13:59,670
<i># Gonna find her #</i>

233
00:14:00,973 --> 00:14:04,033
<i># Gonna find her #</i>
<i># Yeah #</i>

234
00:14:04,109 --> 00:14:07,272
<i>#I've been searchin'#</i>

235
00:14:07,346 --> 00:14:10,008
<i># Uh, I'm searchin'#</i>

236
00:14:10,082 --> 00:14:12,073
<i># Oh, yeah, searchin'#</i>

237
00:14:12,151 --> 00:14:15,917
<i>#Every which way #</i>

238
00:14:15,988 --> 00:14:17,922
Ow!
<i># Oh, yeah #</i>
I'm sorry.

239
00:14:17,990 --> 00:14:20,652
<i>#Searchin'#</i>

240
00:14:20,726 --> 00:14:24,287
<i>#I'm searchin'#</i>
You missed a spot.

241
00:14:24,363 --> 00:14:29,665
<i>#Searchin'every which way #</i>

242
00:14:29,735 --> 00:14:32,067
<i>#But I'm like that... ##</i>

243
00:14:32,137 --> 00:14:34,298
This thing's startin'
to look like a rocket.

244
00:14:34,373 --> 00:14:38,673
Listen to this.
"Weld the washer
to the base of the rocket body,

245
00:14:38,744 --> 00:14:42,612
creating a combustion chamber
and nozzle."

246
00:14:42,681 --> 00:14:45,707
We don't know how to weld.
Weld.

247
00:14:45,784 --> 00:14:48,685
Homer,
your brother's in metal shop.
Maybe he could, uh...

248
00:14:51,590 --> 00:14:54,582
- Do we really need
this nozzle thing?
<i>- For cryin'out loud,</i>

249
00:14:54,660 --> 00:14:56,890
the nozzle's
the most important part.

250
00:14:56,962 --> 00:14:59,726
<i>It directs the flow</i>
<i>of the hot gases!</i>
Hey, cool it, Quentin.

251
00:14:59,798 --> 00:15:02,289
<i>[Roy Lee]</i>
<i>Man, talkin'about</i>
<i>your hot gases.</i>

252
00:15:09,141 --> 00:15:13,168
I don't think your father
would like you sneaking up in
the middle of the night in here.

253
00:15:13,245 --> 00:15:17,272
And I know that he wouldn't
like me welding for you
on company time.

254
00:15:17,349 --> 00:15:19,749
Well, what if I paid
the company for your time?

255
00:15:19,818 --> 00:15:22,218
Homer, I can't.

256
00:15:22,288 --> 00:15:24,756
I would lose my job.

257
00:15:25,824 --> 00:15:27,792
I'm sorry.

258
00:15:27,860 --> 00:15:32,126
Did you see <i>Sputnik</i> go over
the other night?
Nah.

259
00:15:33,999 --> 00:15:37,230
'Cause it was beautiful.

260
00:15:37,303 --> 00:15:40,534
I stood there and watched it
streak across the sky.

261
00:15:40,606 --> 00:15:46,442
And anywhere in the world,
someone could look up
and see exactly what I saw.

262
00:15:46,512 --> 00:15:50,778
For once, it felt like Coalwood
was part of the outside world.

263
00:15:50,849 --> 00:15:56,048
Homer, believe me,
there are much worse places
than Coalwood in this world.

264
00:15:56,121 --> 00:15:59,147
Besides, this is just
a flying piece of steel.

265
00:16:01,160 --> 00:16:04,459
You know, a rocket
took it up there, Mr. Bykovsky.

266
00:16:04,530 --> 00:16:06,760
I don't know. L...

267
00:16:06,832 --> 00:16:09,323
When I was workin'
on this rocket, I felt like,

268
00:16:09,401 --> 00:16:13,861
I felt like I was,
like I was Wernher von Braun.

269
00:16:14,940 --> 00:16:16,931
Let me see.

270
00:16:19,778 --> 00:16:21,712
Homer,

271
00:16:23,415 --> 00:16:25,349
it will be our secret.

272
00:16:27,219 --> 00:16:29,983
Mr. Bykovsky did
a dang good job on this.

273
00:16:30,055 --> 00:16:32,649
Yeah, well,
he used a washer for the weld.

274
00:16:32,725 --> 00:16:35,455
Man, it looks just like it did
in the picture.
Prodigious.

275
00:16:35,527 --> 00:16:37,461
When, uh,
when do we go?

276
00:16:37,529 --> 00:16:39,463
Give me that.
Uh, Saturday...

277
00:16:39,531 --> 00:16:41,692
What is this,
a weapon of some kind?

278
00:16:41,767 --> 00:16:44,998
<i>[Homer Chuckling]</i>
<i>No, sir. It's a,</i>
<i>it's a rocket.</i>

279
00:16:45,070 --> 00:16:47,800
I don't allow dangerous devices
on school grounds.

280
00:16:47,873 --> 00:16:51,969
Mr. Turner, I asked Homer
to bring that to school.
To show it in class.

281
00:16:52,044 --> 00:16:56,538
You know, the boys are
thinkin' about enterin'
that county science fair.

282
00:16:56,615 --> 00:16:59,482
<i>Be careful, gentlemen.</i>
<i>I'm gonna have my eye on you.</i>

283
00:16:59,551 --> 00:17:01,416
Thank you, Mr. Turner.

284
00:17:03,422 --> 00:17:05,617
That science fair is rigged.
All the judges are from Welch,

285
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:08,182
so only the kids from Welch
ever win.

286
00:17:08,260 --> 00:17:11,024
And besides,
science fairs are for geeks.

287
00:17:11,096 --> 00:17:13,030
No offense, Quentin.

288
00:17:13,098 --> 00:17:15,032
Well, it's too bad
you feel that way.

289
00:17:15,100 --> 00:17:18,934
You know, the winners go on
to the National Science Fair
in Indianapolis,

290
00:17:19,004 --> 00:17:22,531
and colleges from all over the
country hand out scholarships.

291
00:17:22,608 --> 00:17:25,668
It's great.
Have a good lunch, boys.

292
00:17:27,746 --> 00:17:30,613
College scholarships
for winning a science fair?

293
00:17:30,682 --> 00:17:32,616
Well, maybe
it's not for you.

294
00:17:32,684 --> 00:17:35,744
W-W-Well,
what do you mean?
Homer, you got a great mind.

295
00:17:35,821 --> 00:17:40,155
But science requires math,
which has never been one
of your favorite subjects.

296
00:17:41,693 --> 00:17:45,060
[Chuckling]
Can't just dream your way
out of Coalwood, Homer.

297
00:17:51,170 --> 00:17:54,333
<i>Auk I.</i>
Stroke of genius, Homer.

298
00:17:54,406 --> 00:17:56,533
It won't fly unless somebody
lights the fuse.

299
00:17:56,608 --> 00:17:58,803
What the hell is auk?

300
00:17:58,877 --> 00:18:00,936
It's a bird that don't fly.

301
00:18:01,013 --> 00:18:03,243
What, kind of like
a parakeet?

302
00:18:03,315 --> 00:18:05,112
Ready?
<i>[Whistle Blowing]</i>

303
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:09,746
Well, Youngstown's
always been fair, Otis,

304
00:18:09,822 --> 00:18:12,586
[Chuckling]
But you're askin' me to lay off
damn near half the town.

305
00:18:12,658 --> 00:18:15,991
The mine
is just not producin'...

306
00:18:16,061 --> 00:18:18,120
the way it was
ten years ago, John.

307
00:18:18,197 --> 00:18:21,132
<i>We're payin'the same labor</i>
<i>for half the tonnage.</i>

308
00:18:21,200 --> 00:18:24,465
What if we were
to open up a new shaft?

309
00:18:24,536 --> 00:18:26,902
<i>[John]</i>
<i>That coal is down there, Otis.</i>

310
00:18:26,972 --> 00:18:29,668
<i>You just, you just</i>
<i>let me go after it.</i>

311
00:18:29,741 --> 00:18:33,006
The Coalwood mine
is givin' out, Mr. Hickam.

312
00:18:37,749 --> 00:18:39,683
Move!

313
00:18:41,253 --> 00:18:44,120
Ten...
[All]
Nine, eight,

314
00:18:44,189 --> 00:18:47,317
seven, six, five,

315
00:18:47,392 --> 00:18:50,122
four, three, two...

316
00:18:52,898 --> 00:18:56,959
Uh-oh.
Holy shit,
it's headed for the mine!

317
00:18:59,404 --> 00:19:02,134
- [Yelling]
- I told you we didn't know
what we were doin'!

318
00:19:02,207 --> 00:19:04,141
I told you!
Oh, no. Oh, no.

319
00:19:04,209 --> 00:19:06,609
<i>[Chattering, Shouting]</i>

320
00:19:08,680 --> 00:19:10,875
<i>[Chattering Continues]</i>

321
00:19:12,084 --> 00:19:14,712
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>I don't believe this.</i>
<i>Go ahead.</i>

322
00:19:14,786 --> 00:19:18,449
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>God in heaven, I thought</i>
<i>it was a guided missile!</i>

323
00:19:18,524 --> 00:19:21,493
<i>[Laughing]</i>
<i>I thought the damn Russians</i>
<i>were attackin'us.</i>

324
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:24,620
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>The boy's in trouble now.</i>

325
00:19:28,800 --> 00:19:32,327
So this is what you been up to
in the basement, huh?

326
00:19:32,404 --> 00:19:35,430
Yes, sir.
Damn, Homer.

327
00:19:35,507 --> 00:19:38,032
You could've killed somebody
with this idiot thing.

328
00:19:38,110 --> 00:19:40,044
I know, sir.
I'm sorry. I was...

329
00:19:40,112 --> 00:19:42,910
Well, Homer here
wants to be a rocket scientist.
Is that it, John?

330
00:19:42,981 --> 00:19:44,915
He has no idea
what he wants to be.

331
00:19:44,983 --> 00:19:49,044
But I know what he is.
He's a menace,

332
00:19:49,121 --> 00:19:51,055
and he's a damn thief.

333
00:19:51,123 --> 00:19:54,058
Dad...
And so is whoever
helped you.

334
00:19:54,126 --> 00:19:56,424
Ike Bykovsky did this,
didn't he?

335
00:19:56,495 --> 00:19:58,895
Don't you ever
let me catch you...

336
00:19:58,964 --> 00:20:02,491
with these fool things
on company property again,
you understand me?

337
00:20:03,869 --> 00:20:06,770
Yes, sir.
Then go home.

338
00:20:18,817 --> 00:20:22,776
[Phone Ringing]

339
00:20:22,854 --> 00:20:25,721
<i>[Thunderclap]</i>
Yeah?
What's your tunnel number?

340
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:30,387
He called me a thief, Ma,
in front of everybody.

341
00:20:30,462 --> 00:20:34,125
I mean, how could he do that?
He was dead wrong
callin' you that.

342
00:20:34,199 --> 00:20:36,133
He'd never have done that
to Jim.

343
00:20:36,201 --> 00:20:39,329
They could catch Jim
stickin' up the company store,

344
00:20:39,404 --> 00:20:42,237
and Dad would probably laugh
and say, "That's my boy."

345
00:20:42,307 --> 00:20:44,707
I know he's hard to understand
sometimes, Homer,

346
00:20:44,776 --> 00:20:46,710
but you have to know
he loves you.

347
00:20:46,778 --> 00:20:49,303
He loves the mine...

348
00:20:49,381 --> 00:20:51,315
more than Jim even.

349
00:20:51,383 --> 00:20:54,375
<i>More than you.</i>
You hush up.

350
00:20:54,453 --> 00:20:57,616
<i>[TV: Screaming]</i>
What's it given him back?

351
00:20:57,689 --> 00:21:00,988
Nothin' but a spot on his lung
the size of a damn quarter.

352
00:21:04,696 --> 00:21:06,926
You don't know
what the mine gives me.

353
00:21:08,066 --> 00:21:10,626
You don't know
'cause you're still a boy.

354
00:21:10,702 --> 00:21:14,763
<i>But, by golly, you're gonna</i>
<i>find out soon enough.</i>

355
00:21:16,608 --> 00:21:18,542
<i>[Thunder Continues]</i>

356
00:21:25,817 --> 00:21:28,081
[Scoffs]
I'm never goin' down there.

357
00:21:28,153 --> 00:21:30,986
<i>[Fork Clatters]</i>

358
00:21:31,056 --> 00:21:33,524
You better have a talk
with your son, Elsie,

359
00:21:33,592 --> 00:21:36,425
<i>'cause he's out of control.</i>

360
00:21:52,177 --> 00:21:56,273
Where's my rocket stuff?
Right where they belong.

361
00:22:12,864 --> 00:22:16,061
<i>[Gunshot]</i>

362
00:22:16,134 --> 00:22:21,071
Quentin, you know, that rocket
went up at least 100 feet.
<i>[Gunshots Continue]</i>

363
00:22:21,139 --> 00:22:23,073
More like 200.

364
00:22:23,141 --> 00:22:25,803
<i>[Gunshot]</i>
God...

365
00:22:27,312 --> 00:22:31,681
Man, will you cut it out,
Roy Lee?
Die, you son of a bitch.

366
00:22:31,750 --> 00:22:34,275
Come on.
My turn now.
Hey, man. What's with you?

367
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:36,446
Man, we should be tryin'
to get in that science fair...

368
00:22:36,521 --> 00:22:38,648
instead of sittin' around here
like a bunch of hillbillies.

369
00:22:38,724 --> 00:22:42,387
I got some really
bad news for you, Homer.
We <i>are</i> a bunch of hillbillies.

370
00:22:42,461 --> 00:22:46,557
Besides, um, didn't your dad
say no more rockets?

371
00:22:46,631 --> 00:22:49,498
No. He said no more rockets
on company property.

372
00:22:49,568 --> 00:22:52,036
Do you realize
how far we'd have to go
to get off company property?

373
00:22:52,104 --> 00:22:54,038
Yeah. We have
to go to Snakeroot.

374
00:22:54,106 --> 00:22:56,438
Snakeroot?
That's eight miles.

375
00:22:56,508 --> 00:22:59,636
It's not <i>that</i> far.
I mean, we could walk
if we have to.

376
00:22:59,711 --> 00:23:03,078
Oh, walk.
That's a fantastic idea.
[Laughing]

377
00:23:03,148 --> 00:23:05,878
Let's go! Come on!
Wake the hell up,
will ya, Homer?

378
00:23:05,951 --> 00:23:08,215
I got about as much chance
of winnin' that science fair...

379
00:23:08,286 --> 00:23:10,550
as you do winnin'
a football scholarship.

380
00:23:10,622 --> 00:23:12,556
I know I'm gonna be
a miner.

381
00:23:12,624 --> 00:23:15,058
I've known my entire life.

382
00:23:15,127 --> 00:23:17,061
What the hell's so bad
about minin' coal?

383
00:23:17,129 --> 00:23:19,063
Nothin', Roy Lee.
Coal minin's great.

384
00:23:19,131 --> 00:23:23,465
That's why your stepdaddy's
the biggest drunk
in West Virginia.

385
00:23:23,535 --> 00:23:27,801
I mean, come on, guys!
You know the mine'll kill ya.

386
00:23:27,873 --> 00:23:30,706
Did you ever hear the story
about how O'Dell's dad died?

387
00:23:30,776 --> 00:23:34,234
- Homer,
will you forget it, man?
- Shut up, Homer.

388
00:23:34,312 --> 00:23:38,112
<i>Apiece of slate</i>
<i>caught him right in the neck</i>
<i>and cut his head clear off.</i>

389
00:23:38,183 --> 00:23:40,378
Bitch! Come on!
[Grunting]

390
00:23:40,452 --> 00:23:42,943
O'Dell!

391
00:23:43,021 --> 00:23:45,990
<i>[Car Horn Honking]</i>
Get off of me!

392
00:23:46,057 --> 00:23:48,924
Hey, fellas.
We're lookin' for U.S. 52.

393
00:23:51,163 --> 00:23:53,097
<i>[Engine Revving]</i>

394
00:23:53,165 --> 00:23:56,225
Uh, fellas?

395
00:23:56,301 --> 00:24:00,067
Uh, just, uh, stay left
at the fork. It's about another
five miles straight ahead.

396
00:24:00,138 --> 00:24:02,003
Thanks.

397
00:24:09,414 --> 00:24:12,349
You fellas see the way
she was lookin' at me?

398
00:24:14,453 --> 00:24:17,854
Man, you all wanna
be coal miners,

399
00:24:17,923 --> 00:24:20,357
you all go ahead
and be coal miners.

400
00:24:32,037 --> 00:24:34,562
There. There.

401
00:24:48,687 --> 00:24:50,621
God's honest truth, Homer,

402
00:24:50,689 --> 00:24:52,850
what are the chances...

403
00:24:52,924 --> 00:24:55,154
of a bunch of kids
from Coalwood...

404
00:24:55,227 --> 00:24:58,025
actually winnin'
the National Science Fair?

405
00:24:58,096 --> 00:25:00,360
A million to one, O'Dell.

406
00:25:00,432 --> 00:25:03,196
That good?

407
00:25:03,268 --> 00:25:06,795
Well, why didn't you say so?
Come on. Give me that.

408
00:25:08,707 --> 00:25:10,641
Quentin.
[Grunts]

409
00:25:16,948 --> 00:25:19,473
What?
[Both Chuckling]

410
00:25:40,405 --> 00:25:43,238
We hiked eight miles
for this?

411
00:25:43,308 --> 00:25:46,072
Oh, it's great.
What should we call it?

412
00:25:46,144 --> 00:25:48,078
How 'bout a slack dump?

413
00:25:48,146 --> 00:25:51,047
<i>[O'Dell]</i>
<i>What about "No Man's Land"?</i>

414
00:25:51,116 --> 00:25:53,584
Cape Coalwood.

415
00:25:53,652 --> 00:25:56,143
I mean, it's perfect.

416
00:25:56,221 --> 00:25:58,519
We could build a blockhouse
over there...

417
00:25:58,590 --> 00:26:00,524
and, and a, and a,
and a launchpad.

418
00:26:01,726 --> 00:26:04,024
<i>And we could even build</i>
<i>a test stand!</i>

419
00:26:16,875 --> 00:26:18,809
<i>[Homer's Voice]</i>
<i>Dear Dr. Von Braun,</i>

420
00:26:18,877 --> 00:26:21,243
<i>our launch site,</i>
<i>which we've named Cape Coalwood,</i>

421
