Mom?

856
00:55:14,844 --> 00:55:18,109
Your father always has to be
the big hero.
<i>[Siren Wailing]</i>

857
00:55:18,181 --> 00:55:21,878
I swear to God,
if he gets killed,
I won't shed a tear.

858
00:55:41,304 --> 00:55:43,238
It's comin' up!

859
00:55:59,456 --> 00:56:01,947
[Screaming, Chattering]

860
00:56:10,633 --> 00:56:12,567
<i>[Woman]</i>
<i>Who-Who is it?</i>

861
00:56:22,912 --> 00:56:26,905
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>It's Ike Bykovsky.</i>
<i>Bykovsky.</i>

862
00:56:31,488 --> 00:56:33,422
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>It's John Hickam!</i>

863
00:56:34,891 --> 00:56:37,257
Dad, Dad!
[Man]
The cable snapped.

864
00:56:37,327 --> 00:56:39,295
May have fractured
his skull!

865
00:56:43,433 --> 00:56:48,200
Get out of the way.
Move back, folks!
Let us through here!

866
00:56:50,106 --> 00:56:55,043
Tell you what, Homer.
A dozen men would've died today
if it hadn't been for your dad.

867
00:57:09,759 --> 00:57:12,193
<i>[Siren Wailing]</i>

868
00:57:40,089 --> 00:57:42,557
Thank you, doctor.

869
00:57:42,625 --> 00:57:45,560
Mm-hmm. Bye-Bye.

870
00:58:03,313 --> 00:58:07,841
The, uh, doctor
says...

871
00:58:07,917 --> 00:58:12,081
there's a chance your dad
could lose his eye.

872
00:58:12,155 --> 00:58:16,717
<i>He has to go to the hospital</i>
<i>in Charleston,</i>

873
00:58:16,793 --> 00:58:19,728
<i>and Olga won't pay</i>
<i>for all of it.</i>

874
00:58:19,796 --> 00:58:24,392
I'm gonna go down to the mine
and ask Jake Mosby
to sign me on.

875
00:58:24,467 --> 00:58:27,402
You can't do that, Jim.
You've got school.

876
00:58:27,470 --> 00:58:31,133
Olga owns this house, Mom,
and half the furniture in it.

877
00:58:31,207 --> 00:58:34,870
If you drop out,
you'll lose your scholarship.

878
00:58:34,944 --> 00:58:39,813
- Homer, I'm the oldest.
It's my responsibility.
- I'll work in the mine.

879
00:58:42,285 --> 00:58:48,053
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

880
00:59:16,085 --> 00:59:19,020
Here you are,
Mr. Turner.
Thank you, Miss Wade.

881
00:59:23,059 --> 00:59:26,620
Mining coal
is an honorable trade,
Mr. Hickam.

882
00:59:29,666 --> 00:59:32,328
Nothing to be ashamed of.

883
00:59:46,849 --> 00:59:49,215
Miss Riley!
Miss Riley!

884
00:59:57,460 --> 01:00:00,395
<i>[Alarm Clock Ringing]</i>

885
01:01:17,573 --> 01:01:19,507
Turn your light on, boy.

886
01:02:05,722 --> 01:02:08,213
Remember when you
gave me these, John?

887
01:02:08,291 --> 01:02:10,782
Carbon crystals
from the mine.

888
01:02:10,860 --> 01:02:14,819
Yeah. Honeymoon.
At Myrtle Beach.

889
01:02:16,199 --> 01:02:20,329
And you said,
"You always wanted diamonds.

890
01:02:20,403 --> 01:02:24,203
But these are
the best I can do.
I wish they were real."

891
01:02:24,273 --> 01:02:28,471
John, I never
wanted diamonds.

892
01:02:34,517 --> 01:02:36,451
This whole year...

893
01:02:36,519 --> 01:02:39,818
has been pretty rough going
down at the mine.

894
01:02:41,457 --> 01:02:44,017
Bad tempers...

895
01:02:44,093 --> 01:02:47,221
and a lot of strike talk.

896
01:02:47,296 --> 01:02:51,733
An accident
makes things worse.

897
01:02:53,202 --> 01:02:55,534
In a way, I guess,

898
01:02:55,605 --> 01:02:59,735
I'm the one who's responsible
for what happened
to Mr. Bykovsky.

899
01:02:59,809 --> 01:03:02,243
Listen to me, Homer.

900
01:03:03,980 --> 01:03:06,312
Last month,

901
01:03:06,382 --> 01:03:10,648
I gave Ike the chance
to go back to the machine shop,

902
01:03:10,720 --> 01:03:12,654
<i>and he turned it down.</i>

903
01:03:12,722 --> 01:03:16,055
<i>Yeah, he stayed in the mine</i>
<i>'cause the money was better.</i>

904
01:03:16,125 --> 01:03:19,151
That was his decision.

905
01:03:19,228 --> 01:03:22,493
<i>You understand me?</i>

906
01:03:22,565 --> 01:03:24,499
Yes, sir.

907
01:03:26,569 --> 01:03:31,871
<i>Well, is mining coal as terrible</i>
<i>as you figured it'd be?</i>

908
01:03:31,941 --> 01:03:34,375
<i>I guess not.</i>

909
01:03:35,945 --> 01:03:38,607
But almost.
[Laughing]

910
01:03:40,082 --> 01:03:42,016
[Coughing]

911
01:03:58,134 --> 01:04:02,628
Everybody says to say hi.
Michael and Billy.

912
01:04:02,705 --> 01:04:04,900
Valentine Carmina.

913
01:04:04,974 --> 01:04:06,908
How about Miss Riley?

914
01:04:06,976 --> 01:04:11,913
She ain't been around much.
She got some new boyfriend
over in Welch.

915
01:04:13,149 --> 01:04:16,641
So, uh, what's it like
down there?

916
01:04:20,223 --> 01:04:22,657
You get used to it
after a while.

917
01:04:23,893 --> 01:04:27,056
Besides, shoveling coal
has got its advantages.

918
01:04:27,129 --> 01:04:29,654
Check this out.

919
01:04:29,732 --> 01:04:33,634
Man, no wonder my stepdad
can slug me so good.

920
01:04:33,703 --> 01:04:36,604
After a month down there,
you'd be able
to knock him out.

921
01:04:39,208 --> 01:04:41,836
Well, I ain't
in no hurry.

922
01:04:41,911 --> 01:04:46,848
<i>[Work Whistle Blowing]</i>

923
01:04:51,721 --> 01:04:54,189
See ya all later.
See ya, man.

924
01:04:54,257 --> 01:04:56,191
See ya, Homer.

925
01:04:57,760 --> 01:05:00,729
In Christ's name,
we pray. Amen.

926
01:05:00,796 --> 01:05:02,730
Amen.

927
01:05:06,969 --> 01:05:10,427
We appreciate the sacrifice
you made here, Homer.

928
01:05:10,506 --> 01:05:14,966
But pretty soon,
you'll be able to go back
and finish up the school year.

929
01:05:16,279 --> 01:05:18,304
I'm not going back
to school.

930
01:05:18,381 --> 01:05:20,781
<i>A few weeks left in the term,</i>

931
01:05:20,850 --> 01:05:23,182
I'll just stay put.

932
01:05:23,252 --> 01:05:26,187
Well, I think you ought
to finish high school.

933
01:05:28,991 --> 01:05:31,221
Well, tell him, John.

934
01:05:32,895 --> 01:05:35,363
Homer's not a boy anymore.

935
01:05:37,566 --> 01:05:40,535
<i>I don't think</i>
<i>I can tell him anything.</i>

936
01:05:40,603 --> 01:05:42,537
<i>[Dishes Clattering]</i>

937
01:05:53,115 --> 01:05:57,245
<i>[Jake] All I'm saying, John,</i>
<i>is the cutoff was not done</i>
<i>proper according to contract.</i>

938
01:05:57,320 --> 01:05:59,254
Well, the company did
what it had to do.

939
01:05:59,322 --> 01:06:01,790
Well, you know the union
won't put up with it.

940
01:06:01,857 --> 01:06:06,021
Just give it a rest, Jake.
It's my first day back.

941
01:06:11,067 --> 01:06:14,867
Hey, Lenny,
how's he doing?

942
01:06:14,937 --> 01:06:16,928
<i>He's a chip</i>
<i>off the old block, John.</i>

943
01:06:17,006 --> 01:06:20,032
It's good
to have you back.
[Chuckling] Thank you.

944
01:06:24,313 --> 01:06:28,977
Hi.
I'm headed toward the face.
You wanna come along?

945
01:06:33,155 --> 01:06:35,885
<i>[John]</i>
<i>Even though I don't have</i>
<i>that piece of paper...</i>

946
01:06:35,958 --> 01:06:39,257
<i>the thing from college...</i>
<i>they listen to me.</i>

947
01:06:39,328 --> 01:06:41,262
You know why?

948
01:06:41,330 --> 01:06:44,265
'Cause you know more
than they do.

949
01:06:44,333 --> 01:06:47,564
You bet your life
I do. Homer.

950
01:06:47,636 --> 01:06:51,402
I know the mine
like I know a man.

951
01:06:51,474 --> 01:06:55,240
Heck, I can take
one look around here...
[Coughing]

952
01:06:57,079 --> 01:06:59,377
Are you all right?

953
01:06:59,448 --> 01:07:01,746
Yeah, I'm not afraid
of a little coal dust.

954
01:07:01,817 --> 01:07:04,809
Hell, Homer,
I was born for this.

955
01:07:04,887 --> 01:07:08,755
I guess
it shouldn't surprise me
that you were too.

956
01:07:08,824 --> 01:07:11,418
Let's go watch 'em
shoot some coal.

957
01:07:18,768 --> 01:07:23,205
Elsie, hold dinner
for a while, will you?

958
01:07:23,272 --> 01:07:25,706
I have to make a call.

959
01:07:31,113 --> 01:07:33,047
Homer,

960
01:07:35,117 --> 01:07:38,814
I was in the store today,
and I heard some talk.

961
01:07:51,600 --> 01:07:54,967
<i>Boy, it's sure hard</i>
<i>to keep a secret in this town,</i>
<i>isn't it?</i>

962
01:07:55,037 --> 01:07:58,029
But I guess I did
a pretty good job.

963
01:07:58,107 --> 01:08:03,010
You know, there's a rumor going
around that I been sneaking off
to Welch to see some beau.

964
01:08:03,079 --> 01:08:06,014
I wish that rumor'd
been true.
Yeah.

965
01:08:06,082 --> 01:08:11,349
They told me Hodgkin's
can go into remission,
so I might have some time.

966
01:08:11,420 --> 01:08:13,980
Is there anything I can do,
Miss Riley?

967
01:08:14,056 --> 01:08:17,355
You can accept
my apology.

968
01:08:17,426 --> 01:08:20,156
For what?

969
01:08:20,229 --> 01:08:22,629
My life's work
is teaching.

970
01:08:22,698 --> 01:08:26,190
And I believed
that if you boys won
that science fair,

971
01:08:26,268 --> 01:08:31,171
got scholarships, went off
and did something great
with your lives,

972
01:08:31,240 --> 01:08:34,038
somehow my life
would have counted
for something.

973
01:08:36,112 --> 01:08:38,046
Homer.

974
01:08:40,883 --> 01:08:43,215
You know what?

975
01:08:43,285 --> 01:08:48,188
Sometimes you really
can't listen to what
anybody else says.

976
01:08:48,257 --> 01:08:51,249
You just gotta
listen inside.

977
01:08:51,327 --> 01:08:54,353
You're not supposed to
end up in those mines.

978
01:08:54,430 --> 01:08:57,888
You know why?
'Cause I think
you made other plans.

979
01:08:57,967 --> 01:09:01,403
I want you
to know something.

980
01:09:01,470 --> 01:09:05,736
I'm proud of you.
I am.

981
01:09:05,808 --> 01:09:08,709
Whatever you choose.

982
01:09:40,809 --> 01:09:42,743
[Ringing]

983
01:09:55,457 --> 01:09:57,891
<i>[Mine Alarm Blaring]</i>

984
01:10:49,945 --> 01:10:54,507
Excuse me, ma'am,
is Quentin home?

985
01:10:59,355 --> 01:11:00,879
Quentin.

986
01:11:05,728 --> 01:11:09,721
Homer, y-you figured
this equation out
by yourself?

987
01:11:09,798 --> 01:11:13,495
Well, if I did the math right.
It proves that you can't...

988
01:11:13,569 --> 01:11:16,538
l-It proves we didn't
start that fire!
<i>Quentin, what're you doin'?</i>

989
01:11:16,605 --> 01:11:20,097
Now, the <i>AUKXIII</i> was
the only one that we couldn't
find that day.

990
01:11:20,175 --> 01:11:22,769
And our best guess
for fall time
with the <i>AUKXII,</i>

991
01:11:22,845 --> 01:11:25,905
which is exactly identical,
was about 14 seconds.

992
01:11:25,981 --> 01:11:28,347
If you help me
with the trig part,
Quentin,

993
01:11:28,417 --> 01:11:32,080
we should be able
to make a good guess
where that rocket landed.

994
01:11:45,768 --> 01:11:48,362
Six thousand,
three hundred
and twenty-eight feet.

995
01:11:49,438 --> 01:11:52,202
One point two miles.

996
01:11:53,542 --> 01:11:55,476
Homer?
Yeah?

997
01:11:58,113 --> 01:12:02,777
Are you gonna tell
Roy Lee and O'Dell
where I live?

998
01:12:02,851 --> 01:12:07,788
It wouldn't matter
if you lived
in the governor's mansion,

999
01:12:07,856 --> 01:12:11,485
they'd still think
you're weird.

1000
01:12:16,065 --> 01:12:18,761
I'll see you at dawn.

1001
01:12:18,834 --> 01:12:21,598
Don't you have to go
to the mine?

1002
01:12:21,670 --> 01:12:24,104
I don't work there
anymore.

1003
01:12:39,621 --> 01:12:41,555
One.

1004
01:12:48,430 --> 01:12:50,364
<i>Two.</i>

1005
01:12:59,808 --> 01:13:01,742
Ninety-nine.

1006
01:13:05,614 --> 01:13:07,548
A hundred seven.

1007
01:13:27,069 --> 01:13:29,333
One hundred
and twenty-six.

1008
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:33,273
That's 6,300 feet.

1009
01:13:33,342 --> 01:13:35,674
It's gotta be
around here somewhere.

1010
01:13:59,568 --> 01:14:02,503
What'd we do wrong?

1011
01:14:02,571 --> 01:14:06,371
I don't know.
L-I'll check the math again.

1012
01:14:16,218 --> 01:14:18,345
Was there a wind
that day?

1013
01:14:18,420 --> 01:14:20,752
L-I don't remember.

1014
01:14:20,823 --> 01:14:22,984
<i>'Cause if there was,</i>

1015
01:14:23,058 --> 01:14:25,686
the wind probably came
from the west...

1016
01:14:25,761 --> 01:14:28,321
which means that
it would've pushed
the rocket...

1017
01:14:30,499 --> 01:14:32,433
right there.

1018
01:14:36,672 --> 01:14:39,004
Prodigious.

1019
01:14:39,074 --> 01:14:41,941
...associated...

1020
01:14:42,010 --> 01:14:43,944
[Students Murmuring]

1021
01:14:47,583 --> 01:14:51,041
Mr. Hayes,
where you off to
in such a hurry?

1022
01:14:51,119 --> 01:14:53,883
Okay, everybody,
back in your seats.

1023
01:14:53,956 --> 01:14:58,416
Miss Stanton, Miss Blue,
let's go, back in your seats.
Mr. Hancock.

1024
01:14:59,495 --> 01:15:01,588
That goes for you too,
Mr. Wilson.

1025
01:15:06,134 --> 01:15:08,068
Miss Riley,
what's going on in here?

1026
01:15:08,136 --> 01:15:11,867
They didn't start
that fire, Mr. Turner.

1027
01:15:11,940 --> 01:15:14,704
In the first place,
you are not a member
of this classroom.

1028
01:15:14,776 --> 01:15:16,801
Neither are you,
Mr. Turner.
<i>[Students Chuckling]</i>

1029
01:15:16,879 --> 01:15:18,813
Why don't you let the boy
defend himself?

1030
01:15:18,881 --> 01:15:22,942
And in the second place,
this rocket proves nothing.

1031
01:15:23,018 --> 01:15:25,816
<i>You've already admitted</i>
<i>having lost a number</i>
<i>of your rockets.</i>

1032
01:15:25,888 --> 01:15:27,947
You cannot prove
conclusively...

1033
01:15:28,023 --> 01:15:31,481
that another one of them
didn't start that fire.
Yes, I can.

1034
01:15:38,467 --> 01:15:41,061
Are we to conclude,
Mr. Hickam, that
since leaving school,

1035
01:15:41,136 --> 01:15:44,401
<i>you've not only become an expert</i>
<i>in rocket science, but in</i>
<i>the field of trigonometry?</i>

1036
01:15:44,473 --> 01:15:46,407
I didn't say
that I was a rock...
<i>Obviously, you learned more...</i>

1037
01:15:46,475 --> 01:15:49,239
in the coal mines
than you did in high school.
[Students Chuckling]

1038
01:15:49,311 --> 01:15:53,805
Let the boy talk.
Go ahead, Homer.

1039
01:15:53,882 --> 01:15:57,909
Now, that fire was near Welch,
just under three miles
from our launchpad.

1040
01:15:57,986 --> 01:16:02,616
And at the time of the fire,
the best that we could do
was 1.2 miles...

1041
01:16:02,691 --> 01:16:05,319
which is exactly where we found
that rocket, Mr. Turner.

1042
01:16:05,394 --> 01:16:09,626
<i>See, Mr. Turner, that rocket</i>
<i>fell for about 14 seconds,</i>
<i>which means...</i>

1043
01:16:09,698 --> 01:16:12,360
that it flew to an altitude
of 3,000 feet...

1044
01:16:12,434 --> 01:16:14,994
<i>according to the equation...</i>

1045
01:16:15,070 --> 01:16:18,471
"S" equals one-half"A"
"T" squared...

1046
01:16:18,540 --> 01:16:22,101
<i>where "S"is the altitude,</i>
<i>"A"is the gravity constant...</i>
<i>or 32...</i>

1047
01:16:22,177 --> 01:16:24,805
and "T" is the time
it took for that rocket
to come back down.

1048
01:16:24,880 --> 01:16:27,872
<i>Velocity equals</i>
<i>acceleration times time.</i>
Get him, Homer, get him.

1049
01:16:27,950 --> 01:16:30,214
Are you following this,
Mr. Turner?
<i>[Students Chuckling]</i>

1050
01:16:30,285 --> 01:16:33,379
All right,
we're all duly impressed.

1051
01:16:33,455 --> 01:16:37,516
But do you mind telling me,
if you did not start that fire,
who did?

1052
01:16:37,593 --> 01:16:39,686
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

1053
01:16:39,761 --> 01:16:41,820
What is it?

1054
01:16:41,897 --> 01:16:46,231
Whatever it is,
i-it's ingenious.
The fins are spring-loaded.

1055
01:16:46,301 --> 01:16:48,531
That isn't a rocket
at all.

1056
01:16:48,604 --> 01:16:51,038
It's an aeronautical flare.

1057
01:16:53,208 --> 01:16:57,201
There's an airport here
in Welch. It's right above
where the fire started.

1058
01:17:06,555 --> 01:17:10,389
Mr. Hickam,
report to my office as soon
as we return to school.

1059
01:17:10,459 --> 01:17:14,589
<i>You do intend to enter</i>
<i>the county science fair,</i>
<i>do you not?</i>

1060
01:17:14,663 --> 01:17:16,824
Yes, sir, we do.

1061
01:17:16,898 --> 01:17:19,526
Well, if you intend
to represent Big Creek,

1062
01:17:19,601 --> 01:17:22,536
you're gonna have to be
enrolled as a student
at Big Creek.

1063
01:17:22,604 --> 01:17:24,538
<i>[Engine Starting]</i>

1064
01:17:24,606 --> 01:17:28,007
"Prodigenous."

1065
01:17:30,846 --> 01:17:33,041
<i>[Homer] Do you think</i>
<i>you can draw well enough</i>
<i>so Mr. Bolden could build it?</i>

1066
01:17:33,115 --> 01:17:35,049
<i>Yep.</i>
<i>Let me see.</i>

1067
01:17:35,117 --> 01:17:37,779
Yeah.
Hey, Homer.

1068
01:17:37,853 --> 01:17:41,016
- Hi, Dad.
- What's this stuff doin' here?

1069
01:17:41,089 --> 01:17:44,388
<i>Mr. Hickam, we didn't</i>
<i>start the fire.</i>
The troopers gave it back to us.

1070
01:17:44,459 --> 01:17:46,757
Yeah, it wasn't even
one of our rockets.
It was an aeronautical flare.

1071
01:17:46,828 --> 01:17:48,887
Y'all go on home now.

1072
01:17:48,964 --> 01:17:50,898
Yes, sir.

1073
01:18:07,482 --> 01:18:12,044
This the reason
you skipped work today?
Yes, sir.

1074
01:18:15,857 --> 01:18:19,452
I thought you put
all this nonsense
behind you, Homer.

1075
01:18:19,528 --> 01:18:22,156
I thought you weren't
gonna be doin' it...
Dad, it isn't nonsense.

1076
01:18:22,230 --> 01:18:24,596
L-I don't wanna
argue with you.

1077
01:18:24,666 --> 01:18:27,032
Look, son,

1078
01:18:27,102 --> 01:18:30,731
I can't even begin to tell you
how proud of you I've been
these past weeks.

1079
01:18:30,806 --> 01:18:35,607
I mean, you've just been
doin' a hell of a job
in that mine.

1080
01:18:35,677 --> 01:18:38,510
You keep goin',
you're gonna have
my job someday.

1081
01:18:38,580 --> 01:18:41,743
Everybody says so.

1082
01:18:42,984 --> 01:18:45,953
You got any idea how proud
that would make me?

1083
01:18:47,222 --> 01:18:49,247
Dad, what l...
<i>[Stammering]</i>

1084
01:18:49,324 --> 01:18:54,990
I guess what I'm sayin' is,
is that if this rocket stuff
is so important to you,

1085
01:18:55,063 --> 01:18:58,931
<i>then so be it,</i>
<i>as long as you're careful.</i>

1086
01:18:59,000 --> 01:19:01,696
Guess there's worse hobbies
you could have.

1087
01:19:01,770 --> 01:19:05,604
<i>But skippin'work,</i>
<i>that's out ofline.</i>

1088
01:19:05,674 --> 01:19:08,404
And you gotta know that.

1089
01:19:08,477 --> 01:19:12,174
So let's go
and get you right
with Jake.

1090
01:19:12,247 --> 01:19:15,045
Tell him you'll work
the hoot owl shift tonight.

1091
01:19:15,117 --> 01:19:16,482
No.

1092
01:19:20,589 --> 01:19:24,184
The coal mine's your life.
It's not mine.

1093
01:19:29,931 --> 01:19:32,798
I'm never going
down there again.

1094
01:19:38,874 --> 01:19:41,308
I wanna go into space.

1095
01:20:04,633 --> 01:20:08,592
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Homer Hickam, Roy Lee Cook,</i>
<i>Quentin Wilson...</i>

1096
01:20:08,670 --> 01:20:10,900
<i>and Sherman O'Dell</i>
<i>of Big Creek High...</i>

1097
01:20:10,972 --> 01:20:13,839
for their ingenious display
of amateur rocket-building
techniques.

1098
01:20:33,995 --> 01:20:36,463
I can't believe
we beat the kid
with the robot dog.

1099
01:20:36,531 --> 01:20:40,194
And I thought
the see-through ear
was gonna win.

1100
01:20:40,268 --> 01:20:42,759
I got Miss Wade workin'
on your travel arrangements,

1101
01:20:42,838 --> 01:20:46,774
so you boys are gonna
have to decide who's goin'
to Indianapolis.

1102
01:20:46,842 --> 01:20:49,538
We're all goin'.
Yeah.

1103
01:20:49,611 --> 01:20:53,479
<i>Son, I wish you could,</i>
<i>but we can't afford</i>
<i>to send all four of you.</i>

1104
01:20:53,548 --> 01:20:57,609
<i>Only one. Let me know</i>
<i>what you decide. I'm gonna</i>
<i>have to know by Friday.</i>

1105
01:20:57,686 --> 01:21:00,678
You boys did
a fine job today.

1106
01:21:11,900 --> 01:21:14,994
I need to borrow a suitcase,
and I'm gonna need
you guys' addresses...

1107
01:21:15,070 --> 01:21:18,437
because I'm gonna
write some postcards.
Oh, you shut up, Roy Lee.

1108
01:21:18,506 --> 01:21:21,498
Come on, you dope.
You know, you're goin',
Homer.

1109
01:21:21,576 --> 01:21:23,510
<i>Yeah.</i>
Yeah.

1110
01:21:23,578 --> 01:21:26,741
Say hello
to the outside world
for us.

1111
01:21:27,349 --> 01:21:29,112
Do we know
what we want?
[All] Yeah!

1112
01:21:29,184 --> 01:21:30,947
Are we gettin' it?
[All] No!

1113
01:21:31,019 --> 01:21:34,887
All right!
All in favor of goin' out
on strike, say "aye"!

1114
01:21:34,956 --> 01:21:36,389
[All]
Aye!

1115
01:21:36,458 --> 01:21:38,790
<i>All right, let's go!</i>
[Shouting]

1116
01:21:38,860 --> 01:21:41,693
<i>All right, shut 'em down!</i>
<i>Let's go!</i>

1117
01:21:41,763 --> 01:21:45,961
<i>Strike! Strike!</i>
<i>Strike!</i>

1118
01:21:46,034 --> 01:21:47,968
[Shouting Continues]

1119
01:22:03,518 --> 01:22:05,645
Well, they sure are
gettin' themselves
worked up.

1120
01:22:05,720 --> 01:22:07,654
Everybody's sayin'
this one's gonna be
a long one.

1121
01:22:07,722 --> 01:22:10,748
And it will,
if I have anything
to say about it.

1122
01:22:10,825 --> 01:22:12,793
Ungrateful
sons of bitches.

1123
01:22:12,861 --> 01:22:16,661
Mom, have you seen
the big green suitcase?
Did you look in the attic?

1124
01:22:16,731 --> 01:22:20,895
Yes, ma'am.
Well, I don't know. John,
you know where the suitcase is?

1125
01:22:23,138 --> 01:22:26,733
How the hell should I know
where the suitcase is?

1126
01:22:26,808 --> 01:22:28,833
<i>I don't know, sug.</i>

1127
01:22:28,910 --> 01:22:30,844
<i>[Mother Murmuring]</i>

1128
01:22:34,149 --> 01:22:36,208
[Sighing]

1129
01:22:41,323 --> 01:22:43,382
[Gunshot,
Glass Shattering]

1130
01:22:43,458 --> 01:22:47,155
- John!
- Y'all stay inside!

1131
01:22:49,230 --> 01:22:53,599
<i>[Tires Screeching]</i>
Vernon!

1132
01:22:53,668 --> 01:22:55,761
<i>[Jim]</i>
<i>I'm gonna kill</i>
<i>that son of a bitch!</i>

1133
01:22:55,837 --> 01:22:57,862
Oh, don't be
a damn fool.

1134
01:22:57,939 --> 01:23:02,706
All right, well,
what are we gonna do?
Nothin'.

1135
01:23:02,777 --> 01:23:06,440
<i>Drunken bastard couldn't hit</i>
<i>the broad side of a barn.</i>

1136
01:23:06,514 --> 01:23:08,675
He tried to kill you, Dad.
Yeah, Dad,
you can't just stand...

1137
01:23:08,750 --> 01:23:11,548
Hey, hey, don't
trouble yourself, Homer.

1138
01:23:11,619 --> 01:23:14,110
You got
more important things
to worry about.

1139
01:23:14,189 --> 01:23:17,955
<i>[John]</i>
<i>Just go look</i>
<i>for your suitcase.</i>

1140
01:23:21,796 --> 01:23:24,788
Forget about it, Homer.

1141
01:23:24,866 --> 01:23:26,800
Shut up, Jim!

1142
01:23:26,868 --> 01:23:31,931
Listen, I'm sorry about
what's goin' on around here,
but it isn't my fault!

1143
01:23:32,007 --> 01:23:34,999
What do you want
from me anyway?
Better watch yourself, Homer!

1144
01:23:35,076 --> 01:23:37,567
If I win at Indianapolis,
maybe I can go to college,

1145
01:23:37,645 --> 01:23:39,704
maybe even get a job
at Cape Canaveral!

1146
01:23:39,781 --> 01:23:42,978
<i>There's nothing here for me!</i>
<i>The town is dyin'!!</i>

1147
01:23:43,051 --> 01:23:45,315
The mine is dyin'!
Everybody knows it here
but you!

1148
01:23:45,387 --> 01:23:48,788
You wanna get out of here
so bad, then go! Go!

1149
01:23:48,857 --> 01:23:50,154
Yeah, I'll go!
Yeah, I'll go!

1150
01:23:50,225 --> 01:23:51,556
Go, go!
I'll go!

1151
01:23:51,626 --> 01:23:56,825
And I'll be gone forever!
I won't even look back!

1152
01:23:59,768 --> 01:24:02,134
<i>[Door Slamming]</i>

1153
01:24:40,041 --> 01:24:42,475
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Welcome to Indianapolis!</i>

1154
01:24:42,544 --> 01:24:45,570
<i>Visitors to the fair</i>
<i>will include prominent members</i>
<i>of every branch...</i>

1155
01:24:45,647 --> 01:24:47,911
<i>of the national</i>
<i>scientific community.</i>

1156
01:24:47,982 --> 01:24:50,280
<i>The fair will be open</i>
<i>to the public</i>
<i>over the next two days.</i>

1157
01:24:50,351 --> 01:24:55,311
<i>The following day,</i>
<i>the judges will arrive</i>
<i>to select the winners.</i>

1158
01:24:55,390 --> 01:25:00,487
By timing the rocket's descent,
we would be able to figure out
just how high the rocket flew.

1159
01:25:03,431 --> 01:25:06,161
Would you like to see?
This is a Delaval nozzle.

1160
01:25:06,234 --> 01:25:08,395
Do any of y'all know
what a Delaval noz...

1161
01:25:19,047 --> 01:25:21,880
Two, please.
The judges always go
for the most expensive exhibits.

1162
01:25:21,950 --> 01:25:23,884
That guy with
the biosphere's gonna win.

1163
01:25:23,952 --> 01:25:27,820
I don't think so.
My money's on the kid
with the rocket display.

1164
01:25:27,889 --> 01:25:30,824
Have you seen it yet?
It's really cool.

1165
01:25:35,864 --> 01:25:38,560
<i>[Woman On P.A.]</i>
<i>Mr. Owens,</i>
<i>to the security office.</i>

1166
01:25:38,633 --> 01:25:40,828
<i>Mr. Owens,</i>
<i>to the security office, please.</i>

1167
01:25:50,078 --> 01:25:53,570
<i>It's not like we got a hell</i>
<i>of a lot of time, Roy Lee.</i>
<i>The judging is tomorrow.</i>

1168
01:25:53,648 --> 01:25:55,582
There's nothin' we can do
without Mr. Bolden.

1169
01:25:55,650 --> 01:25:57,948
And he can't get anywhere
near the machine shop.

1170
01:25:58,019 --> 01:26:01,921
They even took my picture
of Dr. Von Braun.

1171
01:26:01,990 --> 01:26:03,924
They stole everything.

1172
01:26:05,827 --> 01:26:08,261
<i>[Car Horn Honking]</i>

1173
01:26:13,101 --> 01:26:15,626
Leon, what are you doing
back here?

1174
01:26:15,703 --> 01:26:17,864
You know you shouldn't
be seen back here.

1175
01:26:17,939 --> 01:26:20,203
I know, Elsie,
but Homer's in trouble.

1176
01:26:22,110 --> 01:26:24,044
[Shouting]

1177
01:26:35,190 --> 01:26:39,490
Elsie, I don't have the power
to settle this strike.

1178
01:26:39,561 --> 01:26:42,496
The bosses listen to you.
They'll do what you tell 'em.

1179
01:26:42,564 --> 01:26:45,124
I am not gonna crawl
on my belly...

1180
01:26:45,200 --> 01:26:48,761
in front of those
miserable union rats.

1181
01:26:48,836 --> 01:26:51,566
Is that what this
is about, John?
Is this about your pride?

1182
01:26:51,639 --> 01:26:54,107
No, it's about what's best
for Coalwood.

1183
01:26:54,175 --> 01:26:59,238
If this mine
doesn't produce,
then the town dies.

1184
01:26:59,314 --> 01:27:03,148
Think the union gives
a good damn about that?

1185
01:27:03,218 --> 01:27:05,778
They're nothin'
but a bunch of greedy
sons of bitches that...

1186
01:27:05,853 --> 01:27:07,787
Shut up, John.
Just shut up.

1187
01:27:07,855 --> 01:27:11,018
Homer once said
you love the mine more
than your own family.

1188
01:27:11,092 --> 01:27:13,526
And I took up for you
'cause I didn't wanna
believe it.

1189
01:27:13,595 --> 01:27:16,587
Homer has gotten a lot of help
from the people in this town.

1190
01:27:16,664 --> 01:27:19,758
They've helped him build
his rockets, they've gone out
there and watched him fly 'em.

1191
01:27:19,834 --> 01:27:24,134
But not you, John.
You never showed up.
Not even once.

1192
01:27:24,205 --> 01:27:26,264
Now, I'm not asking you
to believe in him,

1193
01:27:26,341 --> 01:27:29,037
but he's your son,
for God's sake, John.

1194
01:27:29,110 --> 01:27:32,204
And I am askin' you
to help him.

1195
01:27:32,280 --> 01:27:34,214
If you don't,
I'll leave you.

1196
01:27:34,282 --> 01:27:37,149
I'll find work.
I'll do whatever it takes
to get away from here.

1197
01:27:37,218 --> 01:27:42,520
I'll live in a tree
to get away from you.
Don't you think I won't.

1198
01:27:44,259 --> 01:27:46,193
Where would you go?

1199
01:27:48,663 --> 01:27:50,597
Myrtle Beach.

1200
01:27:54,102 --> 01:27:58,038
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

1201
01:28:04,245 --> 01:28:07,214
I guess we all know
this isn't gonna fix things,

1202
01:28:07,282 --> 01:28:09,716
uh, at least not for long.

1203
01:28:09,784 --> 01:28:12,344
We know you did
what you could for us.

1204
01:28:12,420 --> 01:28:14,547
Jake.
Thanks.

1205
01:28:14,622 --> 01:28:16,522
Leon.

1206
01:28:16,591 --> 01:28:18,525
Yes, John.

1207
01:28:19,961 --> 01:28:23,727
Don't you have
some work to do?

1208
01:28:36,177 --> 01:28:39,044
It's packed and shipped
and on its way. Be at
the bus station, 8:00 a.m.

1209
01:28:39,113 --> 01:28:41,877
Okay, Mom,
but how'd you...
Your father, Homer.

1210
01:28:41,949 --> 01:28:44,179
It was your father.
Give 'em hell, Homer!

1211
01:28:44,252 --> 01:28:46,186
[Cheering]

1212
01:28:49,123 --> 01:28:52,149
- Good luck, sweetie.
- Bye.

1213
01:28:53,528 --> 01:28:55,462
<i>[Coin Clinks]</i>

1214
01:29:05,440 --> 01:29:07,374
Thanks, Dad.

1215
01:29:20,655 --> 01:29:23,647
<i>[Homer] When</i>
<i>the rocket propellant burns,</i>
<i>it produces a river of gas...</i>

1216
01:29:23,725 --> 01:29:26,216
<i>which flows through</i>
<i>the convergent section</i>
<i>of the nozzle.</i>

1217
01:29:26,294 --> 01:29:28,558
If the river continues
through the nozzle,

1218
01:29:28,629 --> 01:29:30,620
but through the throat
at less than sonic speed...

1219
01:29:30,698 --> 01:29:33,223
that is to say, less than
the speed of sound...

1220
01:29:33,301 --> 01:29:36,634
it becomes compact in the...
compacted in the divergent
section,

1221
01:29:36,704 --> 01:29:38,638
bound in turmoil
and inefficient.

1222
01:29:38,706 --> 01:29:43,302
<i>Lyle Wells and Jean Cooper,</i>
<i>Schrader High School,</i>
<i>McMinnville, Oregon.</i>

1223
01:30:01,562 --> 01:30:05,464
Now, ladies and gentlemen,
the big moment.

1224
01:30:05,533 --> 01:30:09,196
<i>The Highest Scholastic</i>
<i>Achievement Award</i>
<i>for Science.</i>

1225
01:30:09,270 --> 01:30:12,797
<i>The National Science Fair</i>
<i>first prize gold medal...</i>

1226
01:30:12,874 --> 01:30:15,365
<i>goes to Homer Hickam,</i>

1227
01:30:15,443 --> 01:30:18,742
<i>Quentin Wilson, Roy Lee Cook</i>
<i>and Sherman O'Dell,</i>

1228
01:30:18,813 --> 01:30:22,943
<i>Big Creek High School,</i>
<i>McDowell County, West Virginia.</i>

1229
01:30:54,649 --> 01:30:58,050
Tom Webster of Virginia State
College. I wanna talk to you
about a scholarship.

1230
01:30:58,119 --> 01:31:02,249
Jack Palmer, Virginia Tech.
We got the best science program
in the state, buddy, okay?

1231
01:31:02,323 --> 01:31:06,316
Congratulations, son.
Good luck to you.

1232
01:31:08,963 --> 01:31:11,591
What did he say to you?
What did who say?

1233
01:31:11,666 --> 01:31:17,400
Von Braun.
That was Wernher von Braun.
You just shook his hand.

1234
01:31:25,146 --> 01:31:28,206
[Cheering]

1235
01:31:34,589 --> 01:31:37,786
Oh, Homer,
I'm so proud of you.
Thanks, Mom.

1236
01:31:37,859 --> 01:31:41,192
He's not here, hon.

1237
01:31:41,262 --> 01:31:43,696
Where's Miss Riley?

1238
01:32:00,281 --> 01:32:02,215
Hello, Miss Riley.

1239
01:32:05,219 --> 01:32:07,153
Hi, Homer.

1240
01:32:07,221 --> 01:32:09,155
Hi.
Hi.

1241
01:32:11,759 --> 01:32:14,819
Oh!
You did it!

1242
01:32:14,896 --> 01:32:17,990
I knew you would.

1243
01:32:18,065 --> 01:32:22,001
The Rocket Boys
are goin' to college.

1244
01:32:22,069 --> 01:32:24,765
We all got scholarships.
[Chuckling]

1245
01:32:24,839 --> 01:32:27,273
And you know what?

1246
01:32:28,743 --> 01:32:32,474
From now on,
every school year,

1247
01:32:32,547 --> 01:32:34,981
I'm gonna brag
to all my new students...

1248
01:32:35,049 --> 01:32:38,678
about how I taught
Homer Hickam
and the Rocket Boys.

1249
01:32:38,753 --> 01:32:41,313
Maybe one day,

1250
01:32:41,389 --> 01:32:45,587
one of them'll feel
like they can do
what y'all did.

1251
01:32:57,238 --> 01:33:00,173
You know, just,
stuff like that
takes time.

1252
01:33:05,780 --> 01:33:07,714
Will you let me out?

1253
01:33:14,555 --> 01:33:19,322
<i>[John]</i>
<i>What are they doin',</i>
<i>charging Olga for that.</i>

1254
01:33:19,393 --> 01:33:22,021
Hell, I'm going to salvage
something up here?

1255
01:33:22,096 --> 01:33:24,121
Hey, Dad. Hi.
Hello, Homer.

1256
01:33:24,198 --> 01:33:27,827
I just wanted to tell you
how much I appreciate
what you did for me.

1257
01:33:27,902 --> 01:33:31,895
I know it wasn't easy for you,
so thank you.

1258
01:33:31,973 --> 01:33:34,669
A-And we're shootin' off
our last rocket today at 5:00,

1259
01:33:34,742 --> 01:33:38,269
so if you'd like to come
see it...
I got a lot of work to do.

1260
01:33:38,346 --> 01:33:41,679
All right. Well,
I just thought I'd ask.

1261
01:33:44,418 --> 01:33:46,818
Hear you met
your big hero.

1262
01:33:49,156 --> 01:33:51,351
Didn't even know it.

1263
01:33:58,099 --> 01:34:00,033
Look,

1264
01:34:00,101 --> 01:34:03,036
I know you and me
don't exactly see eye to eye
on certain things.

1265
01:34:03,104 --> 01:34:07,700
I mean,
we don't see eye to eye
on just about anything.

1266
01:34:07,775 --> 01:34:12,474
But Dad, I come to believe
that I got it in me to be
somebody in this world.

1267
01:34:12,546 --> 01:34:15,379
A-And it's not because
I'm so different
from you either.

1268
01:34:15,449 --> 01:34:17,849
It's 'cause
I'm the same.

1269
01:34:17,918 --> 01:34:22,617
You know, I can be
just as hardheaded
and just as tough.

1270
01:34:22,690 --> 01:34:26,922
I only hope I can be
as good a man as you are.

1271
01:34:26,994 --> 01:34:30,054
I mean, sure,

1272
01:34:30,131 --> 01:34:33,658
Dr. Von Braun's
a great scientist,

1273
01:34:33,734 --> 01:34:36,168
but he isn't my hero.

1274
01:35:06,467 --> 01:35:08,401
<i>[Elevator Buzzes]</i>

1275
01:35:37,832 --> 01:35:42,292
It's our last rocket.
Yeah, let's do it.

1276
01:35:42,369 --> 01:35:45,304
Wire it up for me, will ya?
I gotta do something.
Yeah.

1277
01:35:47,274 --> 01:35:49,401
<i>Hi, Homer.</i>
Hi.

1278
01:35:49,477 --> 01:35:52,344
Congratulations
on winning
the science fair.

1279
01:35:52,413 --> 01:35:55,678
It's gotta be the most
exciting thing that's ever
happened around here.

1280
01:35:55,750 --> 01:35:58,981
Um, I was thinking,
Homer, if, if you've
got some time...

1281
01:35:59,053 --> 01:36:02,784
Excuse me, Dorothy.
Hi.
Hi.

1282
01:36:06,761 --> 01:36:10,390
Good luck.
Thanks.
[Clears Throat]

1283
